			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/investment-banking/">Investment Banking</a> | <a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/mergers-acquisitions/">Mergers &amp; Acquisitions</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Spain Sells Catalunya Banc to BBVA for $1.6 Billion</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Raphael Minder			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-07-22T14:16:08+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 22, 2014 10:16 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 22, 2014 10:16 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/22/spain-sells-catalunya-banc-to-bbva-for-1-6-billion/" data-title="Spain Sells Catalunya Banc to BBVA for $1.6 Billion" data-description="The auction of the state-owned Catalunya Banc, which was pushed back twice over concerns about its mortgages, helps Spain move closer to cleaning up its banking sector.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/22/business/dealbook/dbpix-caixa/dbpix-caixa-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/22/business/dealbook/dbpix-caixa/dbpix-caixa-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/22/business/dealbook/dbpix-caixa/dbpix-caixa-blog480.jpg" id="100000003014196" width="480" height="298" alt="A Â Catalunya Banc branch in Barcelona, Spain."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="298"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A Â Catalunya Banc branch in Barcelona, Spain.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Andreu Dalmau/European Pressphoto Agency</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">MADRID â Spain has taken an important step toward completing the cleanup of its banking sector by selling the state-owned Catalunya Banc to BBVA for 1.19 billion euros, or $1.6 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The sale, announced on Monday night by the state banking restructuring fund, comes after a difficult and delayed auction process for Catalunya. Spain had to inject more public money into the lender than initially expected to attract bidders.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Catalunya, based in the northeastern region of Catalonia, resulted from the merger of three smaller savings banks, or cajas, that were severely hurt by the 2008 bursting of Spainâs construction bubble. Crippled by bad property loans, Catalunya was nationalized and ended up receiving â¬12 billion of rescue money as part of a broader bailout led by Bankia, the giant lender whose problems plunged Spain into a banking crisis two years ago.   </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After seizing control of Bankia, the government was forced to negotiate a European bank bailout in June 2012 to keep Bankia and others afloat. However, Spain ended up using only â¬41 billion of the available â¬100 billion of European rescue money. The restructuring fund then proceeded to sell the rescued banks after transferring their most troubled property assets to a so-called bad bank that has since been selling them to other investors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even so, the auction of Catalunya was pushed back twice over concerns about its mortgages. Last week, in a final effort to clean up the bankâs portfolio, Spain agreed to inject an additional â¬572 million of public money into a deal with Blackstone, the United States private equity firm, to take over a â¬6.4 billion portfolio of loans.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Under the terms of the takeover by BBVA, the purchase price will be reduced by â¬267 million if BBVA is not satisfied with how the government ends up treating Catalunya&#8217;s deferred tax assets.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The difficult sale of Catalunya helped raise the overall amount of public money used to shore up Spainâs banks to almost â¬108 billion, according to the calculations of Robert Tornabell, a banking professor at the Esade business school in Barcelona.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In retrospect, Mr. Tornabell argued, Spain should have used far more than just two-fifths of the European bailout money because it was available âat cheaper and very long-term ratesâ even if that meant raising Spainâs debt burden. Spain âworried more about keeping its debt ratio low than about not wasting taxpayersâ money,â Mr. Tornabell said.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Spain still has to divest one state-controlled bank, Banco Mare Nostrum, which is expected to happen through a public stock offering. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">BBVA shares climbed more than 2 percent on Tuesday on the news that it had won the auction for Catalunya, reinforcing significantly its presence in a region that accounts for a fifth of Spainâs output.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Francisco GonzÃ¡lez, the chairman of BBVA, said in a statement that âthis deal shows the big trust we have in the recovery of the Spanish economy.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Moodyâs Investors Service, however, maintained its negative outlook for Spanish banks last week. While acknowledging Spainâs economic rebound, which should help banks avoid deeper problems in terms of loan quality on their books, Moodyâs also warned in a report that low European interest rates would prevent Spanish banks from increasing their net interest income significantly.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âSpain&#8217;s real estate sector will continue to weigh on the banking system&#8217;s performance, as the oversupply of residential property continues to depress prices,â Moodyâs wrote.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Spanish banks are set to come under the spotlight again in October as part of a review of European banks conducted by the European Central Bank. Even if Spanish banks were already subject to rigorous and independent scrutiny as part of their European bailout, the recent financing problems of the family that controls Banco EspÃ­rito Santo in neighboring Portugal also rattled investors in Spain and elsewhere this month.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Speaking about the E.C.B. review, Mr. Tornabell said: âI think more surprises could come from Portugal, but I do think Spain has got rid off its biggest problems, including now Catalunya Banc.â</p>
